{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480978"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"134"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486554"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:37:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:37:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"134"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/134"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.4,0.18,0.25,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"134"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106088"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/134"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"134"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88563"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1238"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4707"},{"type":"tags","id":"4708"},{"type":"tags","id":"4709"},{"type":"tags","id":"4820"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"9663"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14024"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36984"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39028"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106088"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up of a sexually transmitted infection screen. The test was performed at the same time as her cervical screening test, the latter which is normal. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Nucleic acid amplification testing is positive for \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E infection. She is asymptomatic and she is not pregnant. She has had the same sexual partner for the past six months. She is commenced on the appropriate treatment but asks whether she needs any follow up testing. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate follow-up plan upon completion of treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat endocervical swab in seven days","Repeat endocervical swabs at 14 days and then three months","Repeat endocervical swab in three months","Repeat endocervical swab in 14 days","Repeat endocervical swabs at seven days and then three months"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAnnual screening for \u003Cem\u003EN. gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E is recommended for all sexually active women aged 25 years or under and for all older women with an increased risk of infection (e.g., a new sexual partner). This patient has asymptomatic urogenital gonorrhoea, as diagnosed on the basis of an endocervical swab analysed by nucleic acid amplification testing. Up to 80% of genital gonorrhoea is asymptomatic in women (10-15% in men), and rectal or pharyngeal infection is also typically asymptomatic.  Patient follow up should be at 1 week post-treatment for discussion of contact tracing and symptom resolution, then with endocervical swabs in 2 weeks and 3 months. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat endocervical swabs in 14 days and then three months\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate follow-up plan. This approach addresses both the need for testing for cure and testing for reinfection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETesting for cure is recommended at 14 days post-treatment for gonorrhoea. This is crucial to ensure that the treatment has been effective, especially given the increasing prevalence of antibiotic-resistant strains of \u003Cem\u003EN. gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E. The 14-day interval allows sufficient time for the antibiotics to clear the infection and for any non-viable genetic material to be cleared from the body, which could otherwise lead to false-positive results if testing is done too early.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETesting for reinfection is recommended at three months post-treatment. This is important because individuals who have been infected with gonorrhoea are at higher risk of reinfection. The three-month test helps to identify any new infections that may have occurred after successful treatment of the initial infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe following are incorrect as they present incorrect testing intervals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat endocervical swab in seven days\u003C/strong\u003E is too early for testing for cure and does not address the need for testing for reinfection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat endocervical swabs at seven days and then three months\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because seven days is too early for testing for cure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat endocervical swab in three months\u003C/strong\u003E only addresses the need for testing for reinfection but misses the important test of cure at 14 days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat endocervical swab in 14 days\u003C/strong\u003E only addresses the test of cure but misses the important test for reinfection at 3 months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that in addition to these follow-up tests, management should include treatment of the patient\u0027s sexual partners and counseling about safe sex practices to prevent reinfection and further transmission of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Some 80% of cases of gonorrhoea in women remain asymptomatic.","Testing for cure is recommended at 14 days post-treatment for gonorrhoea.","Testing for reinfection is recommended at three months post-treatment for gonorrhoea."],"references":["Australian STI Management Guidelines [online]. Available at: http://www.sti.guidelines.org.au/","Lahra M, Enriquez R, George CRR. Australian Gonococcal Surveillance Programme Annual Report 2017. Comm Dis Intel. 2019:43.13. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30982247/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88563"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"134"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88563"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-15T21:07:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-15T21:08:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"134"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106088"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":n